Abstract 

This project focuses on analyzing the frequency response and voltage-current (VI) characteristics of electrical systems using the ADALM1000 (M1K) and a Python-based measurement framework. The approach involves automated signal generation, data acquisition, and analysis using tools such as PySMU, NumPy, and Matplotlib. In addition to basic measurements, the project incorporates FFT-based frequency-domain analysis and transfer function estimation to better understand system behavior. Experimental validation is planned using simple circuits such as RC filters. The system aims to bridge theoretical concepts from Signals and Systems with practical observations, while also considering limitations such as noise and hardware constraints.

1. Introduction

This project lies in the domain of experimental signal processing and system analysis. Understanding how systems respond to different input signals is essential in electronics and signal processing applications. The project focuses on studying system behavior using both time-domain and frequency-domain techniques, supported by programmable hardware.

1.1 Motivation

The motivation is to connect theoretical concepts such as frequency response and system representation with real-world experimental data using programmable tools.

1.2 Scope of the Project

In scope:

